address = {New York, NY, USA},
url = {https://doi.org/10.1145/3672758.3672895},
doi = {10.1145/3672758.3672895},
abstract = {Since the birth of drone technology in the 1920s, its aerospace value, measurement value, and military value have been fully recognized. This paper presents a comprehensive study on the application of drones in disaster management, with a particular focus on fire incidents. We build upon a previously established Analytic Hierarchy Process (AHP) model developed by our team [1], enhancing it to optimize the monitoring area radius, enhancing the efficiency and effectiveness of drones in emergency response and disaster relief operations. The research investigates the sensitivity of monitoring area radius and delves into the impact of environmental factors such as terrain and weather on drone performance. It further explores the strategic deployment of Emergency Operation Centers (EOCs) and the use of repeater drones to extend communication ranges. The core contributions of this paper lie in the development of an innovative drone deployment strategy that improves response times and increases the overall safety and effectiveness of disaster management efforts. Through real-world case studies, including the fire incidents in Australia, we demonstrate the practical advantages of our proposed solutions and discuss the potential for future applications in various disaster scenarios.},
